# CI/CD & Deployment Workflow Analysis

This document explains how the `sfjapi` code moves from a commit in GitLab to a running service in AWS.

## 1. Overview of the Pipeline
The workflow is split between **GitLab** (for code quality and testing) and **AWS** (for building and orchestration).

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[GitLab Push] --> B(GitLab CI: Test/Lint)
    B -->|Success| C[AWS CodePipeline Trigger]
    C --> D(AWS CodeBuild: Docker Build)
    D --> E[Amazon ECR: Image Push]
    E --> F(AWS CloudFormation: Update Stack)
    F --> G[AWS ECS: Rolling Update]
    G --> H{Health Check}
    H -->|Pass| I[Deployment Success]
    H -->|Fail| J[Circuit Breaker: Rollback]
```

## 2. Detailed Steps

### Step 1: GitLab CI (Validation)
- **Files**: [.gitlab-ci.yml](file:///c:/Users/myPC/Desktop/dev/job/sfj/sfjapi/.gitlab-ci.yml)
- **When it runs**: On every push to any branch.
- **What it does**:
    - **Python**: Runs `pytest` (unit tests), `ruff` (SAST/Lint), and `mypy` (type checking).
    - **Node**: Runs `prettier` to check HTML template formatting.
- **If it fails**: The pipeline stops immediately. You will see a "Failed" status in GitLab. Code cannot be considered "safe" for deployment.

### Step 2: AWS CodePipeline (Orchestration)
- **Trigger**: Automatic notification via AWS CodeStar Connection when `main` is updated or a `staging` tag is pushed.
- **What it does**: Orchestrates the transition between Source, Build, and Deploy stages.
- **If it fails**: The pipeline stops. The production/staging environment remains on the old version.

### Step 3: AWS CodeBuild (Build)
- **Files**: [sfjapi.dockerfile](file:///c:/Users/myPC/Desktop/dev/job/sfj/sfjapi/sfjapi.dockerfile)
- **What it does**:
    - Build a multi-stage Docker image using `python:3.12-alpine`.
    - Installs dependencies using `uv sync --frozen`.
    - Tags the image with the Git commit hash and `latest`.
    - Pushes the image to **Amazon ECR**.
- **If it fails**: Usually due to dependency conflicts (e.g., [uv.lock](file:///c:/Users/myPC/Desktop/dev/job/sfj/sfjapi/uv.lock) mismatch) or syntax errors. No new image is created.

### Step 4: AWS CloudFormation (Infrastructure as Code)
- **Files**: [sfj-api-app.yml](file:///c:/Users/myPC/Desktop/dev/job/sfj/sfjapi/devops/cloudformation/sfj-api-app.yml)
- **What it does**:
    - Updates the **ECS Task Definition** with the new image URI from ECR.
    - Triggers the ECS service update.
- **If it fails**: If the CloudFormation template has errors (e.g., invalid IAM permissions or missing parameters), the stack update will fail and stay on the previous state.

### Step 5: AWS ECS (Deployment & Rollback)
- **What it does**:
    - Starts new containers with the updated image.
    - Waits for them to pass **ALB Health Checks**.
    - Gradually stops old containers (Rolling Update).
- **Circuit Breaker**: [sfj-api-app.yml](file:///c:/Users/myPC/Desktop/dev/job/sfj/sfjapi/devops/cloudformation/sfj-api-app.yml) has `DeploymentCircuitBreaker` enabled.
- **If it fails**: If the new version crashes or fails health checks (e.g., cannot connect to Database), ECS automatically **rolls back** to the last known stable Task Definition.

## 3. Observability (OTel Collector)
The stack in [sfj-api-otel.yml](file:///c:/Users/myPC/Desktop/dev/job/sfj/sfjapi/devops/cloudformation/sfj-api-otel.yml) deploys an **AWS OTel Collector**.
- It collects traces and metrics from the application (using the `opentelemetry` libraries seen in [pyproject.toml](file:///c:/Users/myPC/Desktop/dev/job/sfj/sfjapi/pyproject.toml)).
- Sends data to the endpoint configured in Secrets Manager.

## 4. Summary of Failure Impacts
- **GitLab CI Fail**: Prevents bad code from reaching AWS. No impact on live environment.
- **CodeBuild Fail**: Build stops. No new image. Live environment stays as is.
- **ECS Health Check Fail**: **Automatic Rollback**. The system detects the failure and restores the previous working version automatically.
